00:49:44,978 --> 00:49:46,813
I mean, you should take a lesson from him. They don't...

529
00:49:47,939 --> 00:49:49,733
They don't stay up all night worrying.

530
00:49:50,150 --> 00:49:51,067
They figured out

531
00:49:51,067 --> 00:49:53,737
how to get the two of us to do exactly what they want.

532
00:49:53,737 --> 00:49:54,863
They are basically

533
00:49:54,863 --> 00:49:58,742
very sophisticated little parasites when you think about it.

534
00:49:58,742 --> 00:50:01,453
Well, the dumbest creatures are the happiest.

535
00:50:01,453 --> 00:50:02,662
Just look at your mother.

536
00:50:05,540 --> 00:50:07,709
He's really just living the moment.

537
00:50:09,669 --> 00:50:10,921
It's like now.

538
00:50:11,505 --> 00:50:13,757
What could be better than being tucked up here with you?

539
00:50:17,928 --> 00:50:21,681
If I died right now it would be OK.

540
00:50:23,725 --> 00:50:25,393
Well, it wouldn't be OK with me

541
00:50:26,228 --> 00:50:28,605
so why don't you shut up and go change the record.

542
00:50:30,690 --> 00:50:31,817
Good answer.

543
00:50:33,568 --> 00:50:34,694
You know what? I was thinking about taking them up...

544
00:50:34,694 --> 00:50:37,113
...to Denver with me next week if it's okay with you.

545
00:50:38,198 --> 00:50:39,866
It's my mom. She loves them.

546
00:50:40,325 --> 00:50:42,786
Probably that recognition of a similar mind.

547
00:50:46,790 --> 00:50:48,375
You stay there, old man.

548
00:51:19,948 --> 00:51:21,658
Tie in a windsor.

549
00:54:34,059 --> 00:54:38,313
No, I did not forget the gin. I'll see you in ten minutes.

550
00:55:22,649 --> 00:55:25,569
Christopher, would you like it if I killed you?

551
00:55:25,610 --> 00:55:26,653
I don't know.

552
00:55:26,695 --> 00:55:29,197
If you keep this up we're going to find out.

553
00:55:29,197 --> 00:55:31,700
So, why don't you go home and stop shooting people?

554
00:56:03,482 --> 00:56:05,484
I'm so happy to see you.

555
00:56:10,405 --> 00:56:11,531
Come on in.

556
00:56:14,701 --> 00:56:17,662
It smells wonderful. I'm very hungry. Where is Lois?

557
00:56:17,662 --> 00:56:20,373
I gave her the night off. I'm cooking myself.

558
00:56:20,373 --> 00:56:22,667
You are?        Yes, I'm trying something new.

559
00:56:22,709 --> 00:56:24,419
Charley darling, "you cooking' is new.

560
00:56:24,461 --> 00:56:25,420
Don't be smart.

561
00:56:25,420 --> 00:56:28,173
I'm in a good mood tonight. I'm going to be fun.

562
00:56:28,173 --> 00:56:30,884
I've already made two New Year's resolutions.

563
00:56:30,884 --> 00:56:34,429
Resolution one: No more talk that of awful ex-husbands...

564
00:56:34,471 --> 00:56:36,306
..and children who don't give a damn.

565
00:56:36,598 --> 00:56:38,183
And the other one?        One what?

566
00:56:38,183 --> 00:56:39,351
Resolution.

567
00:56:39,726 --> 00:56:40,894
Resolution two:

568
00:56:40,894 --> 00:56:44,439
More smoking and more drinking and screw it all! So come on...

569
00:56:44,481 --> 00:56:45,899
...mix me up a drink.

570
00:56:45,899 --> 00:56:47,651
I'll have a gin and tonic, please.

571
00:56:47,692 --> 00:56:50,821
And watch out baby!        Coming up.

572
00:56:55,575 --> 00:56:57,285
It was sweet of you to come tonight.

573
00:56:57,410 --> 00:56:58,995
Sweet had nothing to do with it.

574
00:57:00,622 --> 00:57:04,835
I needed to see you.      Oh,Geo. Come off it.

575
00:57:05,252 --> 00:57:08,171
Whenever you do something sweet you're too ashamed to admit it.

576
00:57:09,089 --> 00:57:11,258
Here is to our early New Year's resolutions.

577
00:57:15,303 --> 00:57:16,137
Cheers.

578
00:57:18,014 --> 00:57:19,891
What are your resolutions by the way?

579
00:57:21,476 --> 00:57:26,106
To let go of the past completely, entirely, and forever.

580
00:57:28,650 --> 00:57:30,110
Light me up, will you?

581
00:57:38,285 --> 00:57:40,871
Darling, you don't look well.

582
00:57:41,454 --> 00:57:43,957
Do you remember that little heart attack you had last year?

583
00:57:43,957 --> 00:57:44,666
It wasn't a heart attack.

584
00:57:44,666 --> 00:57:46,042
Well whatever it was darling...

585
00:57:46,042 --> 00:57:48,086
...you don't look so hot.

586
00:57:48,086 --> 00:57:51,339
I'm fine. I never felt better.

587
00:57:51,339 --> 00:57:52,632
I'm a little tired. I haven't been sleeping...

588
00:57:52,632 --> 00:57:55,218
Geo, it's normal.

589
00:57:55,886 --> 00:57:57,804
You were with Jim for 16 years.

590
00:57:57,804 --> 00:58:00,682
I think about Richard every day.

591
00:58:00,724 --> 00:58:02,058
It's hard being alone.

592
00:58:03,810 --> 00:58:06,897
At least you have a job and a life.

593
00:58:08,106 --> 00:58:10,567
Let's have a bit of dinner shall we?

594
00:58:11,193 --> 00:58:15,113
Because I've worked so very hard.

595
00:58:15,906 --> 00:58:17,491
What are you talking about?

596
00:58:18,033 --> 00:58:19,534
Seriously, there no such thing as old anymore.

597
00:58:19,534 --> 00:58:22,829
The other day one of my students has called me a senior citizen.

598
00:58:24,080 --> 00:58:25,582
I wouldn't mind if old didn't exist...

599
00:58:25,582 --> 00:58:28,502
...but I'm not sure senior is what I'm aiming for either.

600
00:58:28,543 --> 00:58:29,961
It's all becoming so bland.

601
00:58:29,961 --> 00:58:31,296
It's not why I came to America.

602
00:58:31,296 --> 00:58:33,798
It's like a complete breakdown of culture and manners.

603
00:58:33,840 --> 00:58:35,717
The young ones have no manners.

604
00:58:36,551 --> 00:58:38,094
The other day at the car wash

605
00:58:38,512 --> 00:58:40,430
a young man looked me up and down...

606
00:58:40,430 --> 00:58:43,433
...and actually asked me if I was a natural blonde.

607
00:58:43,433 --> 00:58:45,018
What did you say?        I looked him straight in the eye...

608
00:58:45,018 --> 00:58:48,855
...and said: "Let's just say if I stood on my head...

609
00:58:48,855 --> 00:58:51,149
...I would be a natural brunette with lovely breath.

610
00:58:51,149 --> 00:58:53,026
You didn't!        I did!

611
00:58:54,653 --> 00:58:58,240
And the amusing thing was that it went right over his head!

612
00:58:59,366 --> 00:59:02,202
You know, you had a mouth on you even back in London.

613
00:59:02,202 --> 00:59:04,871
Do you remember that old lesbian who threw her drink over your head...

614
00:59:04,913 --> 00:59:07,290
...because you asked her if she was hung like a donut.

615
00:59:18,885 --> 00:59:19,970
Geo.

616
00:59:19,970 --> 00:59:22,848
We could always go back to London. The two of us.

617
00:59:22,848 --> 00:59:25,934
No, thanks.        You know you miss it.

618
00:59:25,976 --> 00:59:27,352
I miss it sometimes.

619
00:59:28,395 --> 00:59:29,980
Maybe if Jim had lived.

620
00:59:30,897 --> 00:59:31,982
He loved being in England.

621
00:59:31,982 --> 00:59:33,733
He asked us to stay the last time we were there.

622
00:59:33,733 --> 00:59:35,694
Do you really think you would have moved?

623
00:59:38,196 --> 00:59:40,949
I don't know. It's silly to even talk about it. It was only a fantasy.

624
00:59:49,875 --> 00:59:50,876
What's this?

625
00:59:52,127 --> 00:59:53,211
It's my mother's wedding ring.

626
00:59:54,337 --> 00:59:56,381
I found it a drawer when I was cleaning out.

627
01:00:03,763 --> 01:00:06,474
Charley my dear, you and I are both in need of another drink.

628
01:01:38,358 --> 01:01:40,360
Wait! Wait, wait!

629
01:01:49,536 --> 01:01:50,912
I love this!

630
01:01:51,830 --> 01:01:54,291
You're insane!        Come on, old man!

631
01:03:14,079 --> 01:03:14,871
Don't move.

632
01:03:24,089 --> 01:03:24,881
Thank you.

633
01:03:35,350 --> 01:03:39,521
Very smooth cigarette move.        I've always wanted to do that.

634
01:03:41,106 --> 01:03:42,399
You don't even smoke.

635
01:03:42,440 --> 01:03:44,734
Well, not for the last sixteen years. Jim hated it.

636
01:03:46,194 --> 01:03:48,488
What's to stop me now? It's not as if he's gonna to kill me.

637
01:03:55,412 --> 01:03:58,874
This is so nice, lying here with you.

638
01:04:00,834 --> 01:04:02,502
Don't you ever miss this?

639
01:04:03,712 --> 01:04:05,547
What we could have been to each other?

640
01:04:06,339 --> 01:04:09,342
Having a real relationship and kids?

641
01:04:12,637 --> 01:04:17,017
I had Jim.        I know, but I mean a real relationship.

642
01:04:18,185 --> 01:04:19,144
Geo, let's be honest,

643
01:04:19,144 --> 01:04:22,063
what you and Jim had together was wonderful but...

644
01:04:23,440 --> 01:04:26,443
...wasn't it really just a substitute for something else?

645
01:04:29,529 --> 01:04:31,740
Is that really what you think after all of these years?

646
01:04:34,326 --> 01:04:38,622
You think Jim was just some kind of substitute for real love?

647
01:04:42,792 --> 01:04:46,421
Jim was not a substitute for anything.

648
01:04:47,297 --> 01:04:48,423
Do you understand?

649
01:04:49,174 --> 01:04:51,051
There is no substitute for Jim...

650
01:04:51,051 --> 01:04:52,177
...anywhere!

651
01:04:52,802 --> 01:04:55,722
And by the way, what is so real about your relationship with Richard?

652
01:04:55,722 --> 01:04:57,933
He left you after nine years!

653
01:04:59,643 --> 01:05:01,853
Jim and I were together for sixteen years!

654
01:05:01,853 --> 01:05:03,897
And if he hadn't died we would still be together!

655
01:05:04,314 --> 01:05:05,941
What the hell is not real about that?

656
01:05:06,316 --> 01:05:08,151
I'm sorry. I'm sorry, I'm sorry.

657
01:05:08,735 --> 01:05:10,487
I know how much the two of you loved each other.

658
01:05:12,155 --> 01:05:15,242
I suppose I'm just jealous that you and I never had that kind of love.

659
01:05:19,246 --> 01:05:21,540
Actually, I've never had that kind of love with anybody.

660
01:05:24,000 --> 01:05:26,336
I don't think Richard ever loved me...

661
01:05:26,837 --> 01:05:27,796
...except for the way I looked.

662
01:05:27,796 --> 01:05:29,673
And Clay...

663
01:05:30,173 --> 01:05:32,133
I don't know. You raise a child and love it...

664
01:05:32,133 --> 01:05:34,094
...and then when they are old enough they just leave.

665
01:05:35,387 --> 01:05:37,180
Charley, there is nothing wrong with your life.

666
01:05:37,180 --> 01:05:38,598
You just like feeling sorry for yourself.

667
01:05:38,598 --> 01:05:39,933
It's one of your great pleasures.

668
01:05:39,933 --> 01:05:42,227
And it's not one of yours?

669
01:05:42,227 --> 01:05:44,187
You're as pathetic as I am.

670
01:05:44,187 --> 01:05:47,023
Feeling sorry for myself is definitely not one of my great pleasures.

671
01:05:47,023 --> 01:05:48,441
Well, it's not one of mine either.

672
01:05:48,441 --> 01:05:50,402
I don't like feeling sorry for myself one bit.

673
01:05:50,443 --> 01:05:52,279
I tried to hold onto Richard for so long...

674
01:05:52,320 --> 01:05:54,364
...even when it was obvious to everyone but me that it was over.

675
01:05:54,364 --> 01:05:55,949
And now Clay is grown up.

676
01:05:55,949 --> 01:05:58,743
I mean, what am I doing here Geo? Tell me, what?

677
01:05:58,743 --> 01:06:01,329
You have plenty of friends. You'll be fine.

678
01:06:01,538 --> 01:06:03,623
Yes, I have friends. But none of them need me.

679
01:06:03,623 --> 01:06:04,457
And yes I have you

680
01:06:04,499 --> 01:06:07,460
and if you weren't such a goddamn poof we could have all been happy!

681
01:06:14,134 --> 01:06:16,303
I only have you now because you lost Jim.

682
01:06:16,678 --> 01:06:17,971
Soon I'll lose you to someone else.

683
01:06:17,971 --> 01:06:19,598
It's not as easy for a woman.

684
01:06:19,639 --> 01:06:21,475
I've done everything the way I was supposed to and...

685
01:06:21,475 --> 01:06:23,894
...all I have to keep me company is a bottle of gin.

686
01:06:24,394 --> 01:06:26,396
Maybe you should try donuts with your gin.

687
01:06:27,814 --> 01:06:28,899
Screw you.

688
01:06:32,110 --> 01:06:33,987
Charlotte, you are dramatic.

689
01:06:34,988 --> 01:06:36,323
I swear you really almost had me.

690
01:06:36,323 --> 01:06:39,159
A tiny tear was beginning to form in the corner of my eye.

691
01:06:40,452 --> 01:06:41,411
Now stop it.

692
01:06:42,162 --> 01:06:45,248
You are still breathtakingly beautiful.

693
01:06:46,416 --> 01:06:48,210
When you can be bothered to get up and out of bed...

694
01:06:48,251 --> 01:06:50,504
...and you stop whimpering about everything for five minutes.

695
01:06:52,130 --> 01:06:55,175
Go to London. Change your life.

696
01:06:55,175 --> 01:06:57,636
If you're not happy being a woman then stop acting like one.

697
01:06:58,011 --> 01:06:59,429
You have all the answers.

698
01:07:00,680 --> 01:07:02,349
No, I don't have any to mention.

699
01:07:03,225 --> 01:07:05,727
If you're so smart why don't you have something new in your life?

700
01:07:06,019 --> 01:07:07,312
Take that position at Stanford.

701
01:07:07,312 --> 01:07:08,980
You complain about that little school

702
01:07:08,980 --> 01:07:10,565
but you could go anywhere you want.

703
01:07:10,565 --> 01:07:12,234
I think what I've done has been worthwhile.

704
01:07:13,860 --> 01:07:15,362
I'm sorry, I'm sorry.

705
01:07:15,362 --> 01:07:16,613
I shouldn't have said that.

706
01:07:18,490 --> 01:07:20,951
As much as I dread it, I think I will go back to London.

707
01:07:20,951 --> 01:07:22,035
Why do you dread it?

708
01:07:23,119 --> 01:07:24,913
When I lived in London last I was young.

709
01:07:24,913 --> 01:07:26,623
I was fresh, I was everything.

710
01:07:27,582 --> 01:07:31,002
Coming to America was such a dream, it was the icing on the cake.

711
01:07:31,711 --> 01:07:33,713
Going home is defeat.

712
01:07:34,256 --> 01:07:36,633
None of it really worked out the way I'd planned.

713
01:07:37,050 --> 01:07:39,261
Most things don't work out the way people plan.

714
01:07:41,763 --> 01:07:42,889
You're just living in the past.

715
01:07:42,889 --> 01:07:44,724
You need to start thinking about your future.

716
01:07:45,475 --> 01:07:48,436
Living in the past is my future.

717
01:07:48,728 --> 01:07:51,314
It doesn't have to be yours. You're a man.

718
01:07:53,150 --> 01:07:55,360
And you're a bore tonight.

719
01:07:56,319 --> 01:07:59,614
Can't we just feel sorry for ourselves a little bit longer?

720
01:08:00,448 --> 01:08:01,992
Let's have another drink.

721
01:08:01,992 --> 01:08:03,326
I don't think so. I have to go.

722
01:08:03,326 --> 01:08:04,161
Come on. Walk me out.        Please, please!

723
01:08:04,161 --> 01:08:07,914
Come on, I have to!        No, this was such fun! No.

724
01:08:16,631 --> 01:08:18,341
When will I see you again?

725
01:08:20,385 --> 01:08:23,972
Aren't you going to England?        I'll never do that!

726
01:08:23,972 --> 01:08:26,016
It's far too much effort.

727
01:08:26,683 --> 01:08:28,018
Besides,

728
01:08:28,018 --> 01:08:32,189
I don't think Jim would want me to leave you here in LA all alone.

729
01:08:32,522 --> 01:08:34,232
Don't worry about me. I'll be fine.

730
01:08:34,274 --> 01:08:35,692
I've got all the answers. Remember?

731
01:08:36,568 --> 01:08:38,111
What are you doing this weekend?

732
01:08:39,696 --> 01:08:41,781
I think I might just be very quiet.

733
01:08:44,409 --> 01:08:47,662
You never really did take me seriously, did you George?

734
01:08:47,913 --> 01:08:51,291
I tried to Charley. Remember? A long time ago.

735
01:08:52,876 --> 01:08:54,711
It didn't really work out, did it?

736
01:08:57,172 --> 01:08:58,131
No, Charley.

737
01:09:05,680 --> 01:09:06,348
Sleep tight.

738
01:09:50,934 --> 01:09:54,271
Patrick, a beer and a packet of Lucky Strike, please.

739
01:10:39,191 --> 01:10:39,983
Excuse me.

740
01:10:55,874 --> 01:10:57,042
It's too hot in there.

741
01:10:58,376 --> 01:10:59,127
Yes, it is.

742
01:11:00,170 --> 01:11:02,589
Would you like a cigarette?        No thanks, I don't smoke.

743
01:11:03,840 --> 01:11:07,886
This place is really crowded.        Well, it is Saturday night.

744
01:11:09,304 --> 01:11:10,180
It's usually as bad as this.

745
01:11:10,180 --> 01:11:12,432
People normally just stop by and pick someone up

746
01:11:12,432 --> 01:11:13,934
and then head on down the beach.

747
01:11:14,935 --> 01:11:16,394
Yeah. It's pretty wild out there.

748
01:11:17,020 --> 01:11:18,772
I'm surprised the cops don't break it up.

749
01:11:19,314 --> 01:11:22,108
Is it always like that?        Since the war ended.

750
01:11:23,276 --> 01:11:25,570
It's pretty great actually. It's kind of pagan.

751
01:11:27,531 --> 01:11:29,658
I'm Jim.        I'm George.

752
01:11:29,658 --> 01:11:30,617
Pleased to meet you Jim.

753
01:11:30,617 --> 01:11:32,994
I'm sorry, I'm supposed to meet some friends but I can't find them.

754
01:11:34,246 --> 01:11:36,122
I just needed to get out of the house

755
01:11:36,122 --> 01:11:38,500
but the lure of a cold beer got to me.

756
01:11:39,376 --> 01:11:40,502
Do you live hereby?

757
01:11:40,502 --> 01:11:41,461
Canyon.

758
01:11:42,546 --> 01:11:44,422
For how long?        Since 38.

759
01:11:44,422 --> 01:11:46,675
Where are you from?        Colorado.

760
01:11:48,093 --> 01:11:51,805
I really like it here. It's close to beach.

761
01:11:53,056 --> 01:11:54,975
I think I might stay after I'm discharged.

762
01:11:56,143 --> 01:11:59,729
I don't know, maybe I'm a bit of a pagan.

763
01:12:04,109 --> 01:12:05,652
After you.        No.

764
01:12:12,325 --> 01:12:13,076
Sorry.

765
01:12:21,209 --> 01:12:23,545
Well, hello.        Hi.

766
01:12:25,338 --> 01:12:27,048
Do you buy me a drink?

767
01:12:28,884 --> 01:12:30,177
I think I'm taken.

768
01:12:32,220 --> 01:12:35,390
Too bad, too bad.

769
01:12:37,851 --> 01:12:39,102
Do you want another beer?

770
01:13:36,993 --> 01:13:40,330
Patrick, a bottle of scotch and a pack of Lucky Strikes to go, please?

771
01:13:51,174 --> 01:13:52,342
Patrick, cancel that.

772
01:14:04,479 --> 01:14:05,856
Well, hello Mr. Potter.

773
01:14:06,857 --> 01:14:07,732
Hello, sir.

774
01:14:09,734 --> 01:14:12,154
What are we drinking?        Scotch.

775
01:14:13,321 --> 01:14:14,156
Okay.

776
01:14:20,620 --> 01:14:21,997
I come here all the time.

777
01:14:22,706 --> 01:14:25,167
I live just around the corner, but then you knew that.

778
01:14:25,167 --> 01:14:26,626
On Camphor Tree Lane.

779
01:14:33,425 --> 01:14:34,759
You're still carrying that around.

780
01:14:37,637 --> 01:14:40,140
One must always appreciate life's little gifts.

781
01:14:44,936 --> 01:14:46,313
So, what are you doing here?

782
01:14:47,105 --> 01:14:49,107
Just out for a ride on my bike.        Is that all?

783
01:14:50,192 --> 01:14:51,026
I don't know.

784
01:14:51,443 --> 01:14:52,652
Were you looking for me?

785
01:14:53,737 --> 01:14:55,947
Maybe. I don't know.

786
01:14:56,531 --> 01:14:58,575
I feel like my head's stopped up with stuff.

787
01:14:58,575 --> 01:14:59,868
What kind of stuff?

788
01:14:59,868 --> 01:15:02,078
Like, the stuff you were talking about today in class.

789
01:15:02,078 --> 01:15:03,914
That is definitely not important.

790
01:15:03,914 --> 01:15:06,500
No, it is important. Your class is great.

791
01:15:06,541 --> 01:15:10,712
But somehow we always seem to get stuck talking about the past.

792
01:15:11,338 --> 01:15:12,923
The past just doesn't matter to me.

793
01:15:13,256 --> 01:15:16,843
The present?        I can't wait for the present to be over.

794
01:15:17,552 --> 01:15:18,929
It's a total drag.

795
01:15:19,554 --> 01:15:22,015
Well, tonight is the exception.

796
01:15:23,642 --> 01:15:24,392
What?

797
01:15:25,393 --> 01:15:28,688
Tonight, yes! The present, no!

798
01:15:29,272 --> 01:15:30,524
Let's drink to tonight.

799
01:15:31,024 --> 01:15:31,942
Tonight.

800
01:15:34,778 --> 01:15:36,863
So if the past doesn't matter and the present is a total drag.

801
01:15:36,863 --> 01:15:37,948
What about the future?

802
01:15:38,990 --> 01:15:41,743
What future? Cuba might just blow us up.

803
01:15:42,536 --> 01:15:43,870
Death is the future.

804
01:15:44,371 --> 01:15:46,331
I'm sorry. I don't mean to be depressing.

805
01:15:46,373 --> 01:15:48,625
It's not depressing. It's not depressing, it's true.

806
01:15:48,667 --> 01:15:51,419
It may not be your immediate future but it's what we all share.

807
01:15:52,504 --> 01:15:53,797
Death is the future.

808
01:15:55,048 --> 01:15:56,258
You're right, I guess.

809
01:15:56,258 --> 01:15:59,219
If one is not enjoying one's present there isn't a great deal to...

810
01:15:59,219 --> 01:16:01,096
...suggest that the future should be any better.

811
01:16:01,972 --> 01:16:03,431
Yeah, I've thought that before.

812
01:16:04,349 --> 01:16:07,769
But the thing is you just never know.

813
01:16:08,728 --> 01:16:09,646
Look at tonight.

814
01:16:14,317 --> 01:16:15,485
Actually...

815
01:16:16,278 --> 01:16:18,238
...I feel really alone most of the time.

816
01:16:19,239 --> 01:16:20,907
You do?        Yeah.

817
01:16:21,658 --> 01:16:23,076
I've always felt this way.

818
01:16:23,535 --> 01:16:26,246
I mean we're born alone, we die alone.

819
01:16:26,955 --> 01:16:28,165
And while we're here

820
01:16:28,415 --> 01:16:31,668
we are absolutely, completely sealed in our own bodies.

821
01:16:32,419 --> 01:16:33,461
Really weird.

822
01:16:35,046 --> 01:16:36,840
Kinda freaks me out to think about it.

823
01:16:37,507 --> 01:16:40,594
We can only experience the outside world

824
01:16:40,802 --> 01:16:42,637
through our own slanted perception of it.

825
01:16:44,598 --> 01:16:46,433
Who knows what you're really like?

826
01:16:46,975 --> 01:16:48,852
I just see what I think you're like.

827
01:16:49,561 --> 01:16:51,605
I'm exactly what I appear to be.

828
01:16:54,107 --> 01:16:55,317
If you look closely.

829
01:17:02,115 --> 01:17:04,367
You know the only thing that has made the whole thing worthwhile...

830
01:17:06,786 --> 01:17:07,746
...has been those...

831
01:17:08,788 --> 01:17:09,456
...few times

832
01:17:09,456 --> 01:17:12,709
that I've been able to really, truly connect with another human being.

833
01:17:16,755 --> 01:17:18,423
I had a hunch about you, sir.

834
01:17:18,882 --> 01:17:20,634
You did?        Yes, sir.

835
01:17:21,301 --> 01:17:23,804
I had a hunch you might be a real romantic.

836
01:17:29,559 --> 01:17:32,521
You know, everyone keeps telling you that...

837
01:17:32,521 --> 01:17:35,398
...when you're older, that you'll have all this experience.

838
01:17:35,398 --> 01:17:36,983
Like it's some great thing.

839
01:17:37,651 --> 01:17:38,652
That's a load of shit.

840
01:17:39,152 --> 01:17:41,321
I think I've actually just gotten sillier and sillier.

841
01:17:41,613 --> 01:17:43,406
Really?        Absolutely.

842
01:17:43,740 --> 01:17:46,910
So, all your experience is useless.

843
01:17:48,203 --> 01:17:49,454
No, I wouldn't say that.

844
01:17:50,872 --> 01:17:52,165
As our friend Mr. Huxley says:

845
01:17:52,165 --> 01:17:53,708
Experience is not what happens to a man.

846
01:17:53,750 --> 01:17:56,002
It is what a man does with what happens to him.

847
01:17:58,755 --> 01:18:00,674
Let's go swimming.        Okay.

848
01:18:02,008 --> 01:18:04,636
What?        It was a test.

849
01:18:04,845 --> 01:18:07,055
I thought you were bluffing about being silly so...

850
01:18:07,722 --> 01:18:10,100
...I said to myself I'll suggest

851
01:18:10,100 --> 01:18:12,853
doing something completely outrageous.

852
01:18:12,936 --> 01:18:15,313
And if he resists, if he even hesitates

853
01:18:15,355 --> 01:18:16,940
then I know he's full of shit.

854
01:18:18,942 --> 01:18:20,527
Well, I wasn't. Were you?

855
01:18:22,237 --> 01:18:23,572
Hell, no!

856
01:18:41,548 --> 01:18:43,758
Come on sir. I'll help you down.

857
01:18:45,719 --> 01:18:46,511
Let's go.

858
01:19:34,100 --> 01:19:35,685
Come on, sir.

859
01:20:09,261 --> 01:20:10,011
Sir?

860
01:20:11,012 --> 01:20:11,972
Sir?

861
01:20:22,649 --> 01:20:24,067
That's enough for now, sir.

862
01:20:25,777 --> 01:20:28,446
I'm fine.        I'm cold. Come on.

863
01:20:42,002 --> 01:20:43,670
Can we go back to your place, sir?

864
01:20:44,379 --> 01:20:46,673
Of course. Where else?

865
01:20:47,591 --> 01:20:49,968
Where else.        Are you out of your mind?

866
01:20:50,510 --> 01:20:54,014
What's the matter?        You can't get home like that!

867
01:20:54,014 --> 01:20:55,807
We're invisible, don't you know that?

868
01:20:58,018 --> 01:21:00,645
You know sir, they ought not to let you out on your own.

869
01:21:00,896 --> 01:21:02,689
You're liable to get into real trouble.

870
01:21:03,440 --> 01:21:04,441
I excel at it.

871
01:21:05,150 --> 01:21:06,610
Your forehead is bleeding.

872
01:21:31,343 --> 01:21:33,929
The bathroom is just down the hall if you would like to take a shower.

873
01:21:35,514 --> 01:21:37,182
Aren't you taking a shower too, sir?

874
01:21:37,224 --> 01:21:39,976
I'm fine. I'm English. We like to be cold and wet.

875
01:21:41,144 --> 01:21:43,313
First, I think that we need to take care of that cut, sir.

876
01:21:43,313 --> 01:21:44,815
Do you have any band-aids?

877
01:21:48,944 --> 01:21:52,405
Going camping, sir?        I'm fine, really.

878
01:21:53,532 --> 01:21:55,242
Stay there. I'll be right back.

879
01:22:39,703 --> 01:22:40,495
Sit up.

880
01:22:43,039 --> 01:22:44,124
Tilt your head back.

881
01:23:09,691 --> 01:23:11,860
Well sir, I'm afraid this time you don't have...

882
01:23:11,902 --> 01:23:14,362
...the excuse of mescaline to explain your band-aid.

883
01:23:16,907 --> 01:23:19,034
I think we should get you out of those wet clothes.

884
01:23:22,204 --> 01:23:23,038
Yes, sir.

885
01:24:56,506 --> 01:24:58,467
You're not too cold?        I'm great.

886
01:24:59,676 --> 01:25:02,846
Would you like a drink?        A beer, sir. If you have one.

887
01:25:02,846 --> 01:25:05,182
I'm afraid that's all we have.

888
01:25:05,765 --> 01:25:06,933
Two beers coming up.

889
01:25:21,740 --> 01:25:22,866
You live here all by yourself, sir?

890
01:25:22,866 --> 01:25:23,617
I do now.

891
01:25:24,493 --> 01:25:26,995
I used to share this place with a friend. He was an architect.

892
01:25:27,704 --> 01:25:31,166
Man, guys my age dream about the kind of setup you've got here.

893
01:25:31,166 --> 01:25:33,960
I mean, what more can you want?

894
01:25:33,960 --> 01:25:37,297
You get to be left alone and come and go as you please.

895
01:25:39,341 --> 01:25:41,176
Is that's your idea of the perfect life?

896
01:25:41,176 --> 01:25:43,345
What's the matter, sir? Don't you believe me?

897
01:25:43,887 --> 01:25:45,931
If you're so keen on the idea living by yourself...

898
01:25:45,931 --> 01:25:47,682
...where does Lois fit into this plan?

899
01:25:48,183 --> 01:25:51,061
Lois? What's she got to do with anything?

900
01:25:51,895 --> 01:25:54,022
I got the impression that you and she were together.

901
01:25:57,234 --> 01:26:00,946
Not really. She is kind of cool and...

902
01:26:01,071 --> 01:26:02,405
...we're good friends but...

903
01:26:05,242 --> 01:26:08,578
I think what you really want to ask me is if we sleep together.

904
01:26:09,704 --> 01:26:11,748
And do you?        We did. Once.

905
01:26:11,748 --> 01:26:13,124
Why only once?

906
01:26:13,834 --> 01:26:15,961
I didn't say only once, I said once.

907
01:26:17,420 --> 01:26:19,756
Come on, the last thing I want to talk about right now is Lois.

908
01:26:20,590 --> 01:26:21,591
What time is it?

909
01:26:24,511 --> 01:26:26,138
My watch seems to have stopped.

910
01:26:33,687 --> 01:26:35,313
Do you want me to go?

911
01:26:36,231 --> 01:26:38,483
You must be kidding. Go, get us another beer.

912
01:26:40,485 --> 01:26:41,653
Is that an order, sir?

913
01:26:44,114 --> 01:26:45,365
You're damn right it is.

914
01:26:57,002 --> 01:26:58,044
Pathetic.

915
01:27:00,297 --> 01:27:01,465
Did you say something, sir?

916
01:27:06,303 --> 01:27:07,471
Why are you here?

917
01:27:10,182 --> 01:27:15,479
Why did you get to the office and ask secretary for my address?

918
01:27:17,606 --> 01:27:21,985
I just wanted to see you someplace other than school.

919
01:27:23,069 --> 01:27:23,904
Why?

920
01:27:27,699 --> 01:27:29,326
Sometimes I think I'm crazy

921
01:27:29,367 --> 01:27:31,578
cause I see things so differently than everyone else.

922
01:27:32,913 --> 01:27:34,289
I feel like I can talk to you.

923
01:27:36,291 --> 01:27:39,169
To be honest sir, I was also worried about you today.

924
01:27:44,090 --> 01:27:44,841
Me?

925
01:27:46,259 --> 01:27:47,511
What's to be worried about?

926
01:27:49,221 --> 01:27:49,971
I'm fine.

927
01:27:59,856 --> 01:28:00,607
I'm...

928
01:28:02,484 --> 01:28:03,443
I'm fine.

929
01:30:47,858 --> 01:30:52,737
A few times in my life I've had moments of absolute clarity.

930
01:30:55,198 --> 01:30:57,242
When for a few brief seconds...

931
01:30:58,201 --> 01:31:00,495
...the silence drowns out the noise...

932
01:31:00,537 --> 01:31:03,915
...and I can feel rather than think.

933
01:31:04,875 --> 01:31:07,210
And things seem so sharp...

934
01:31:08,003 --> 01:31:10,046
And the world seems so fresh...

935
01:31:11,590 --> 01:31:14,426
...as though it had all just come into existence.

936
01:31:34,905 --> 01:31:37,240
I can never make these moments last.

937
01:31:38,158 --> 01:31:39,493
I cling to them...

938
01:31:39,493 --> 01:31:41,244
...but like everything they fade.

939
01:31:43,830 --> 01:31:45,665
I've lived my live on these moments.

940
01:31:47,501 --> 01:31:49,169
They pull me back to the present...

941
01:31:51,546 --> 01:31:52,172
...and I realize that

942
01:31:52,172 --> 01:31:56,676
everything is exactly the way it was meant to be.

943
01:34:16,566 --> 01:34:20,153
And just like that it came.
